To begin, we can find $\frac{q}{r} \cdot \frac{s}{r}$: $$ \frac{q}{r} \cdot \frac{s}{r} = \frac{q\cdot s}{r\cdot r} = \frac{qs}{r^2}. $$Similarly, we can find $\frac{q}{r} \cdot \frac{s}{t}$: $$ \frac{q}{r} \cdot \frac{s}{t} = \frac{q\cdot s}{r\cdot t} = \frac{qs}{rt}. $$But $\frac{s}{t} = \frac{1}{2}$, so substitute to get $$ \frac{q}{r} \cdot \frac{s}{t} = \frac{qs}{rt} = \frac{q}{r} \cdot \frac{1}{2} = \frac{q}{2r}. $$Combining this with our first equation $\frac{q}{r} = 9$, we find: $$ \frac{qs}{rt} = \frac{q}{2r} \Longrightarrow 2q = 9t. $$Divide both sides by $q$ and by $9$ to solve for $\frac{t}{q}$: \begin{align*}
\frac{2q}{9t} &= 1 \\
\frac{t}{q} &= \boxed{\frac{9}{2}}.
\end{align*}
